"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.5.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.5.2</span> Tunic, shirt</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">כֻּתֹּנֶת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kutoneth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:4\">EXO 28:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:39\">EXO 28:39</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:40\">EXO 28:40</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod29:5\">EXO 29:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod29:8\">EXO 29:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:27\">EXO 39:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod40:14\">EXO 40:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:7\">LEV 8:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:13\">LEV 8:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev10:5\">LEV 10:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:4\">LEV 16:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra2:69\">EZR 2:69</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh7:69\">NEH 7:69</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh7:71\">NEH 7:71</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">χιτών</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chitōn)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:63\">MRK 14:63</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0039_priest_tunic.jpg\" alt=\"Priest wearing a tunic\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Priest wearing a tunic (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The tunic was another undergarment worn by the High Priest and his fellow priests. It went over the shorts, but from the waist up it was next to the skin, and over top of it went the robe. It was a kind of shirt and probably had long sleeves and reached nearly to the ankles. It was woven of linen. It was probably pulled over the head and was held in place by a sash wound around the waist. See also <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">6.3 Shirt, tunic&lt;REALIA:6.3&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In ordinary usage the Hebrew word <em>kutoneth</em> refers to an everyday article of clothing worn by men and women alike and was probably a sort of “shirt.” The <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> rendering “coat” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:4\">EXO 28:4</a>) is misleading since this piece of clothing was not an outer garment but one worn underneath other clothing and next to the body. <em>Kutoneth</em> has often been translated “tunic” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New English Bible (1970)\">NEB</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Bible (1970)\">NAB</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr>). “Shirt” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>) will be the closest equivalent in many languages. According to <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:4\">EXO 28:4</a>, the tunic was “embroidered” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>). For translating the word “embroidered,” see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.5.3.11 Embroidered cloth, needlework&lt;REALIA:1.5.3.11&gt;</a>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
